commentBody:
@Connie 
Exactly my response: WOW Wow wow... I was sure that even if I figured this out I would have to hunt for a simple typo but came out 12+ minutes below my average. 

Well done Dylan!

@Barry Ancona

Glad to know that worms can bore through stone tablets! Did you solve on paper?

A four-letter rebus entry is mighty small on a phone sceen. Just wondering . . .

@john ezra

"Not where he eats, but where he is eaten."
Ah, Will, in the end we're all WORM Chow.

@Classic Hip-Hop Fan

Hold that thought. I don't know if John Ezra, Cat Lady Margaret and I will be doing POY stuff this year. But I'm sure whoever does it will be happy to get your nomination at the appropriate time.

Thanks!

@Emmy

Slightly envious, and happy for a fellow solver's success!

[sigh] They'll be another one tomorrow. 😉

@Charles Engelke

"The term "rootle" means to dig into the ground with the snout, typically used in reference to animals like pigs. It can also imply searching or rummaging through something, as in "rootling around". The word is derived from the root "root" and is often used in British English."
-----Wiktionary

@Kelp
Add me to the list of left coast feminists surprised at that cluing. 
But I do know I live in a bubble, and thank Goddess for that.

@Steve L

Gosh, all that and you cracked it before your clan came after you with forks and pitchforks!

My hat is off to you!

@Steve L

It's so frustrating when it closes on you. I've had it happen so many times, even in one sitting. Never used to disappear like that. 

Anyhow, I don't know what I am, a newbie plus maybe, but I loved this one! Couldn't solve it last night because we went to see Mousetrap, which was recently a clue for WESTEND.  ☺️

@RP
I admire your patience!  I can't imagine devoting two and a half hours to a puzzle.  I managed over 39 minutes but with at least sixteen cheats.  I failed to make the cheat ticks on my note paper, so don't really know how many cheats.  All the rebuses were among them, certainly.  And then afterwards I had to study the puzzle to see how the answer fragments changed places.

I admire the cleverness of the creator, this is an amazingly complex puzzle!

@Sam F

I have this image of that fuzzy bird going through a set of rollers, and someone collecting the liquid that come out.
UGH!

@Dave K.

You can think not. Or you can make friends with Google. 

<a href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/rootle" target="_blank">https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/rootle</a>

@David Pearce

You and Tom Hanks!

<a href="https://www.thechurchsagharbor.org/some-of-toms-typewriters-from-the-collection-of-tom-hanks" target="_blank">https://www.thechurchsagharbor.org/some-of-toms-typewriters-from-the-collection-of-tom-hanks</a>

@David Pearce

Just go into Staples or Best Buy and see if you can find one.

@Beth

The fact that they're being exhibited, museum-style, proves the clue to be correct.

@Dutchiris

Same problem here. Two bad letters elsewhere.

Unwilling to do extensive flyspecking.

@Lynda

You need to take a look at Settings in the app. When you have the puzzle page open on your phone, Settings is the gear icon on the top right. When you open that, you will probably see that Show Overlays is turned off.

You should turn Show Overlays ON in order to see any special features in the puzzle, including the colored dots in this puzzle.

@Lynda
And on Android phone WITHOUT the app there is no Show Overlays option (at least I've never been able to find it) but the special effects always show up just fine.
So sorry for your trouble. This was a not-to- be-missed puzzle. POY candidate for sure.

@Steve L

Thanks!

When I was solving the puzzle (and after I had gotten the trick), I wondered how I could write it up in an understandable way. It’s nice to know I succeeded.

@dan
@Steve L

I think dan is right.  There is no other reason for including "bug" in the puzzle title other than the connection of WORM and bug.

On the other hand, the title is still clever.  For me, this is a nit too small to pick.

@Kelp

Agreed, that was an excellent choice of illustration.
I have a soft spot for Magritte's paintings, don't know why. But I don't think I've seen this one before.

@Heidi

“ Even the rebus-haters seem to like this one! (Or, at least, admire it.)”


It’s still early.

@SP
No SP it is not what I meant or implied. That’s why I termed it a ‘nit’, also why I stressed that it was correct as per the clue. I repeat, the connotations of such words have been used historically as slurs, which is why I find them a tad uncomfortable. But nowhere in my comment did I so much as hint that they should be struck from the language.

Your apology is accepted. Perhaps in future you could take a breath and reread a comment before you dive in. I’m all for healthy debate, but you completely misunderstood my point.

@JohnM

If they didn't throw more experienced solvers a bone like this every once in a while, they could risk alienating their most loyal patrons.  

I think it's only fair to mix it up a bit.  Anyone who would stomp off because of a challenge every once in a while probably wouldn't be sticking around very long anyway.

@Barry Ancona

In most cases, circles are not colored so I didn't think to look.

In any case, I like working without a net.

@Ian Hookham
@Steve L
I suspect that the poster just put in the first letter of the rebuses, and therefore didn't really "solve" it.  If you put in the rebuses properly, you'll see that all the answers use "all the letters."

@Skeptical1
Anyone who would call this beautiful puzzle "sloppy" is someone who is revealing more about themselves than about the puzzle.

@Xword Junkie

ROOTLE has appeared before, recently enough for me to recall that it was unfamiliar to many, and denounced by some, despite being a gimme for me.

It's the frequentative form of  ROOT. Last time, I described as being the sort of thing you do when hunting for a specific small item amid many other small items, in an overful drawer, handbag or toybox.

@Oikofuge

Thanks. I must have failed to notice ROOTLE the last time it appeared. I'm certainly not questioning its legitimacy.

I wonder if this word is more common on your side of the Atlantic?

@Vaer

Hmmm. Odd. ROOTLED? ROOTLING? ROOTLES? A British poster chimed in to say that my definition was also her understanding.
If only there were some sort of 21st century search facility here, I'd be able to find my previous comment just by looking for "Oikofuge" and "handbag"!

@Vaer

Oooh, sarcasm. Love it.

My email trash is set to clear after 30 days, so no help there.

@Xword Junkie

I'm now coming round to the idea that the discussion of ROOTLE was part of a more general discussion about BrE words that a North American commentator was unfamiliar with. Given the report from @Vaer, I have to deduce that "rootle" hadn't actually appeared in the puzzle, but came up in the associated discussion. 

So apologies for misleading you.

@Laura Stratton

Laura, to say this puzzle doesn’t test your vocabulary and is merely a gimmick is super dismissive of how brilliantly clever it is. 

If you only do crosswords for the ‘words’ and not the ingenuity, then maybe spend your Sundays doing something else.

@RozzieGrandma

I remember that Rice-A-Roni jingle quite clearly from my 1960s childhood TV watching. 

The flavor can’t be beat!

@Dave
I can appreciate the sentiment, but I would counter with the simple fact that it’s a *puzzle*. It’s supposed to be difficult to some degree, and require work and thought to figure out. If you just want an easy crossword that you’ll always be able to solve, stick to Mondays. If you don’t want any work at all, relax by watching TV.  But coming to complain that a puzzle is “too hard” simply because YOU yourself didn’t get it, just comes across as… well, whiny. 

I haven’t seen any name-calling on this thread anywhere?

@Mark
Some people do come here to celebrate their successes, and why shouldn’t they? Bragadocious? Mean spirited.
If we should  “always feel free to comment, vent, complain, or whatever”  then isn’t it just as fair to express pleasure  as it is to whine?

@Dave

I wonder whether part of the frustration when solving online is an implication that the puzzle should be solved in a day? 

I started off solving these without that pressure, from book collections of NYT Sunday puzzles. I could happily spend a couple of weeks on one, work on it for an hour or so then put it down and come back a few days later. And if I couldn't ever get it, I'd look at the answer key. That's how I first figured out how rebuses work in the context of crossword land.

@Elle
When I use the rebus button it takes as many letters as I enter, and I can read the whole thing. I use an iPad.  I tried it on my phone and it also accepts all letters, but it’s quite small and have to expand to read it.
Have you tried entering more than one letter?

@Jennifer
A jingle that has "jingling bells."
"Ding, ding, ding, The San Francisco treat!"

@jennie
I love that word, though!
Maybe a bit more British than American English...

@MOL

Maybe that explains it. I thought of that word immediately but didn't trust it and left it blank for quite awhile.

I read a lot of British English mystery novels, currently reading Ann Cleeves.

@Mike

Holy molely, I feel a tunnel love for this one. 


